This project analyzes a simulated e-commerce dataset containing:

40,000+ orders

100,000+ line items

5,000 customers

600+ products

9 relational tables

The objective is to practice SQL and derive meaningful business insights.

â­ 1. Revenue & Customer KPIs

Total Revenue: Derived from all order items multiplied by unit price.

Total Orders: 40K+ orders across multiple years.

Total Customers: ~5K unique buyers.

Insight: Revenue is heavily concentrated among a smaller subset of repeat buyers, which suggests that retention and loyalty programs would yield high ROI.

ğŸ“… 2. Monthly Revenue Trends

Revenue displays consistent seasonality.

Clear peaks occur during holiday months (Novâ€“Dec).

Slower periods appear mid-year.

Insight: Marketing spend should be shifted toward Q4, with experimentation in offseason months.

ğŸ›’ 3. Top Customers

The top 10 customers contribute disproportionately to total revenue.

Many consistently purchase high-value products.

Insight: Personalized outreach (discounts, early access, loyalty rewards) could significantly boost LTV.

ğŸ“¦ 4. Product & Category Performance

A small set of products drive the majority of revenue.

Certain categories consistently outperform others.

Insight: Prioritizing inventory and advertising toward these high-performers is recommended.

ğŸ”„ 5. Returns Behavior

Return rates differ significantly by category.

Electronics and apparel categories show higher return percentages.

Certain return reasons cluster around specific suppliers.

Insight:
Addressing quality issues or setting better expectations on sizing/specs could reduce returns.

ğŸšš 6. Shipping Efficiency

Delivery times vary across carriers.

Some carriers consistently deliver faster but at higher shipping cost.

Insight:
Optimize shipping partners by balancing speed vs. cost per region.

ğŸ’™ 7. Customer Lifetime Value (LTV)

High-LTV customers tend to reorder in cycles.

Most revenue comes from repeat customers, not one-time buyers.

Insight:
Retention strategies (emails, bundles, subscriptions) would likely improve profitability.
